shared_text:
CCX Media
September 9 at 9:15 AM ¬∑

2020 CCX Hall of Fame Special

Four athletes who played their high school sports in the northwest suburbs are the newest members of the CCX Sports Hall of Fame. Hopkins High School grad Taylor Anderson, Sam Dower and Krista VandeVenter from Osseo Senior High School and A.J. Tarpley of Wayzata High School are the newest inductees into our Hall. The Hall of Fame, started in 2004, now includes 68 former athletes and coaches.

post_text: Hats off to all of the staff who helped make summer learning a success! The six weeks of learning, engagement, thinking creatively and working online wrapped up this week! post_text: Congratulations Tara and Olivia! üíôüíõ#TrojanPride #WeAreWayzata #WayzataWellness
shared_text:
Wayzata High School
August 3 at 1:42 PM ¬∑

Shout out to Tara Haas and Olivia Mundahl, both seniors at WHS! Olivia and Tara presented at the 2020 NatStuCo Virtual Conference on July 24. The conference included 5000 student leaders and advisors from all 50 states as well as 26 countries. More than 200 participants logged on to watch Tara and Liv present, ‚ÄúHow to Host a Survivor Week‚Äù. Wayzata High School has hosted a Survivor Week for 9 years as a fundraiser for WHS Fund-A-Need. Schools across the country have heard about the legendary WHS tradition and want to create something similar in their own communities. After submitting an application to present, NatStuCo approved their request and Tara and Liv did an outstanding job representing Wayzata High School. #TrojanPride #WHSHereForYou #WeAreWayzata

Off-season training has started for high school athletes in several sports, including football.

The Wayzata Trojans returned to the practice fields on June 15th. Because of the COVID-19 pandemic, football workouts are different this year. Instead of weight room training the athletes are working on conditioning and weight training through the use of medicine balls and weightlifting resistance bands.

In the weeks following the killing of George Floyd, many families have asked what they can do and where they can find resources to guide conversations with their children around race and racism.

We want to extend an invitation to you to receive weekly emails with resources for your family ‚Äì books and articles to read, videos to watch and discuss, and more. We're sharing the resources, you decide what's right for your family.
Register for weekly email: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSd17J2-Z_wG15VpdpaXUDah-2TmLgVfXsMDFCVd6bd-n5No5Q/viewform

Free meals pickup Tuesday! #WeAreWayzata #TrojanPride #WayzataWellness

Also, follow this link for more information about P-EBT
https://mn.gov/dhs/p-ebt/

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a temporary food benefit available to Minnesota families with children who would have received free or reduced-price meals if schools were open. Families with eligible children will receive a one-time payment of $325 per child on a new or existing EBT card to help fill the gap created by a loss of school meals.

To ensure that you are receiving all of our district text messages...you need to enter your cell phone number into Skyward Family Access AND text YES to 67587
Additionally, add 763-745-5019 to your contacts as WPS Emergency Phone Message.
For all emails, be sure we have your email address and add communications@wayzataschools.org and noreply@wayzataschools.myenotice.com to your safe contacts list.

In the meantime, all of the information we have sent out to this point can be found here: https://www.wayzataschools.org/covid19

post_text:
Dear WPS Staff and Families,

Governor Tim Walz has announced that all Minnesota schools will be closing due to the coronavirus effective Wednesday, March 18 until Friday, March 27. In addition, Wayzata Public Schools will be closed for students Monday, March 16 and Tuesday, March 17, and March 30 through April 6 due to our previously scheduled spring break.

We understand how challenging this situation is for everyone and we are doing our very best to make sure the needs of all of our students and staff are met. Please watch for an update coming later today with more details.

Thank you for your continued partnership and support as we navigate this quickly evolving situation.

Sincerely,

Chace B. Anderson
Superintendent

Attention Parents! Early Kindergarten Entrance!
Children who are five years old by September 1 are eligible to begin kindergarten. We offer early kindergarten entrance for children who turn five between September 2 and October 15 and reside in our district at the time of application.
Children who demonstrate superior intellectual ability, high levels of academic achievement, and social/emotional development well-advanced for their age may be considered for early kindergarten entrance.
Applications will be accepted through May 1.
Learn more: www.wayzataschools.org/district/teaching-learning/gifted-talented
